Denison’s Arts and Jazz Fest features live jazz throughout downtown. Discover Denison, Denison Arts Council, local school jazz bands, and over a dozen local art vendors worked together to provide this unique experience. © Randy Sedlacek Denison, Texas 2025 Great American Main Street Awards Winner Denison, Texas Raton, New Mexico 2025 Great American Main Street Awards Winner Raton, New Mexico Furniture maker Robby Pederson and his custom furniture store, RVP ~ 1875 , is one of Jefferson’s top tourism entities, connecting the history of the community and region with modern experiences and functionality. © Matt Wetrich Jefferson, Iowa 2025 Great American Main Street Awards Winner Jefferson, Iowa Visitors enjoy the newly renovated Cotton Avenue Plaza, where a Confederate monument stood before being relocated to Rose Hill Cemetery. © DSTO Moore Macon, Georgia 2024 Great American Main Street Awards Winner Macon, Georgia Family-owned and operated businesses like Fountain Alley work daily to create the perfect experience for their customers. © Austin Sims Madison, Indiana 2024 Great American Main Street Awards Winner Madison, Indiana Monroeville, Alabama © Pierce Drones Monroeville, Alabama 2024 Great American Main Street Awards Winner Monroeville, Alabama Featured Resource Main Street Disaster and Resilience Toolkit Get the tools to plan for, prepare for, and recover from natural disasters in your community. Download the toolkit here. Marion, IA © Uptown Marion Recent News and Stories Main Spotlight: The Economics of Fall Foliage Tourism Fall foliage tourism has a substantial economic impact on small towns and rural areas nationwide. Learn how Main Streets can leverage their leaves to boost their communities this fall. September 9, 2025 Vibrant fall colors drive tourists to towns like Stowe, Vermont. Photo by BackyardProduction. Insights Staff Spotlight: Exploring Arkansas with Lisa Mullins Thompson Lisa shares reflections about eight Arkansas communities that recently received assessment visits August 28, 2025 Lisa Mullins Thompson traveled across the state with Main Street Arkansas. Photo by Lisa Mullins Thompson. Storytelling Main Spotlight: 5 Tips for Running a Successful Grant Program Our grantmaking team shares their advice to help you run a successful grant program and expand your impact in your community. August 26, 2025 Mercado del Pueblo Business Incubator received a grant from The Hartford Small Business Accelerator Grant Program. Photo courtesy of PRCC . How-to Just Dropped: New Courses in the Main Street America Academy Deepen your knowledge, bring your vision to life, and expand your impact with our latest Main Street America Academy course. Whether you’re navigating your first grant or hosting a community event, the Local Main Street Leader Launching module is designed to support your growth without burning out. August 20, 2025 Turn plans into progress with the Local Main Street Leader Launching courses. Photo by KandE Productions. Announcement Vintage Vibes, Digital Drive with Rachael Kehler, Peppermint Stick Candy Store Join host Matt Wagner for his conversation with Rachael Kehler, owner of The Peppermint Stick Candy Store in Boyertown, Pennsylvania. In this episode, Matt and Rachael discuss her journey to entrepreneurship, leveraging nostalgia as a marketing tool, small town tourism, and more. August 20, 2025 Storytelling Main Spotlight: Building Shared Priorities to Unlock Growth Main Street America has partnered with the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation to explore the impact of the Capital Absorption Framework in Main Street communities in Virginia and Wisconsin. August 19, 2025 Participants in Wisconsin gather for a workshop in West Allis, WI . Photo by Main Street America. Insights Community Spotlight: How Nashville’s Entrepreneurs are Driving Community Transformation Discover how small businesses are breaking barriers in our Breaking Barriers to Business (B3) series, starting with a powerful spotlight on Nashville’s local changemakers. August 14, 2025 Nashville, Tennessee © Breaking Barriers to Business ( B 3 ) Storytelling Made on Main: DANE Fragrance As part of a new series on Main Street America’s online store, Shop Main Street, we're highlighting the stories behind the amazing brands, makers, and producers along our Main Streets. Today, we’re highlighting DANE Fragrance, a perfumery based in Ukiah, California. August 14, 2025 Storytelling Spotlight on a Main Street Board Member: The Visionary Spirit of Maxine Clark Meet Maxine Clark—entrepreneur, philanthropist, and board member at Delmar Main Street in St. Louis, Missouri—and hear Erin's takeaways from their conversation about advocacy, resiliency, and leadership. August 7, 2025 From left: Gayla Roten, State Director at Missouri Main Street; Felice McClendon, Executive Director at Delmar Main Street; Maxine Clark, Delmar Main Street Board Member and Chief Inspirator at Delmar DivINe; Erin Barnes, President and CEO at Main Street America. Photo courtesy of Maxine Clark. Storytelling Main Spotlight: How a Fresh Start Revitalized Downtown Maryville’s Market Scene Farmers markets are fantastic tools to support local businesses, drive traffic downtown, and build community connections. Learn how Downtown Maryville built their market from an idea to a success. August 5, 2025 The Downtown Maryville Market brings people of all ages to Maryville’s Main Street. Photo courtesy of Downtown Maryville. How-to Main Spotlight: Walking Together to Connect a Community Charles Town Now brings people together with an event that celebrates the importance of nothing. Discover how they organized the event and its lasting impact on the community. July 29, 2025 The Charles Town community gathered for their largest Walk About Nothing on June 4 th . Photo courtesy of Charles Town Now. Storytelling Strengthen Local Economies with the 2025 Supporting Small Businesses on Main Street Course Generously sponsored by U.S. Bank, this live, three-week course centers the real challenges of entrepreneurs and equips Main Street leaders with invaluable insights and practical tools to respond. Register today! July 28, 2025 Oregon City, Oregon. Photo by Adam Wickham. Announcement Florence, South Carolina. Photo by True Light Photography. “ Our downtown would not be the thriving ecosystem it is today without our community’s steadfast alignment with the Main Street Approach.” - Hannah Davis, Main Street Program Director, Florence, S.C. Main Street Capital Corporation (MAIN) Skip to main content Skip to footer News Contact Careers Home About About Lower Middle Market Solutions Private Credit Solutions Company History Corporate Social Responsibility Team Executive Committee Lower Middle Market Team Private Credit Team Finance, Legal, Compliance, & Accounting Board of Directors Portfolio Companies Lower Middle Market Private Credit Investors IR Overview News & Events Company Information Financial Information Listed Securities Information SEC Filings Governance For Business Owners What Makes Us Different Who We Invest In Why Businesses Partner With Us How We Invest Minority Recapitalization News Contact Careers Search Search Main Street A True Financial Partner Main Street Capital, based in Houston, Texas, has helped over 200 private companies grow or transition by providing flexible private equity and debt capital solutions. Privately-held businesses turn to us because we are Main Street, not Wall Street--we build relationships and tailor transactions to meet the unique needs of our portfolio companies and their owners. Why Main Street? Customized Capital Solutions We provide “one-stop” capital solutions (private debt and private equity capital) to lower middle market companies and debt capital to middle market companies. Main Street's lower middle market companies generally have annual revenues between $10 million and $150 million. While Main Street's middle market debt investments are made in businesses that are generally larger in size. Through our two business segments, we offer entrepreneurs, business owners, management teams and financial sponsors a number of advantages to help each business realize its full potential and generate wealth for its owners. Learn More Portfolio Companies A seasoned institutional investor, we partner with existing management teams, entrepreneurs and business owners to facilitate management buyouts, majority and minority recapitalizations, growth financings and acquisitions. We have a proven track record established over 20 years of partnering with companies that operate across diverse industry sectors and geographic regions to provide a “one-stop” capital providers of private equity and private debt solutions. In Fiscal year 2005 Main Street Winter Haven introduced a new initiative the Benefactor Program.  As a Benefactor, a Business pledges to Main Street Winter Haven an annual $5,000 investment for a minimum of two years. What is a Visionary Benefactor? A Visionary Benefactor is a Main Street Winter Haven Benefactor who has made the commitment to support the program for a minimum of ten years .  We applaud their vision for a economically, socially and culturally vibrant downtown. Downtown Winter Haven has a promising future.  We invite you to help us in reaching its full potential. To become a Benefactor of Main Street Winter Haven please call (863) 295-9422. Main Street Winter Haven is a 501(c)(3) designated non profit corporation, thus making your benefactor contribution tax deductible. Main Street Winter Haven receives 100% of your contribution.
